        <dc:title>MODELLING THE AGGREGATE LOAD BEHAVIOUR OF EUROPEAN REGIONS AND ITS INFLUENCE ON DYNAMIC AND STATIC VOLTAGE STABILITY</dc:title>
        <dcterms:abstract>In a large-scale transmission network, such as the European power system, the regional characteristics of electrical demand may have an impact on local voltage stability. The dynamic load behaviour depends on the sectoral composition of demand, which is subject to regional and seasonal variation. An aggregate load model is presented, which accounts for the sectoral characteristics of 210 European regions for all hours a year from the perspective of the high, medium, and low voltage levels. The proposed load model is used to better understand the influence of regional characteristics on voltage recovery during a short-circuit event, as well as the static point of voltage collapse. Several countries are considered in terms of their sectoral composition, to represent intermediate regions or such dominated by the industry and households. Moreover, the dynamic load model is benchmarked against two static load models, assuming a constant power (PQ) load or a constant impedance (Z) load. The conducted study demonstrates that regional differences in the composition of demand highly impact local voltage stability.</dcterms:abstract>
        <dc:date>2021-09</dc:date>
        <z:libraryCatalog>IEEE Xplore</z:libraryCatalog>
        <dc:identifier>
            <dcterms:URI>
                <rdf:value>https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/9692499/</rdf:value>
            </dcterms:URI>
        </dc:identifier>
        <dcterms:dateSubmitted>2025-09-12 11:18:19</dcterms:dateSubmitted>
        <bib:pages>2391-2395</bib:pages>
        <bib:presentedAt>
            <bib:Conference>
                <dc:title>CIRED 2021 - The 26th International Conference and Exhibition on Electricity Distribution</dc:title>
            </bib:Conference>
        </bib:presentedAt>
    </rdf:Description>
    <bib:Memo rdf:about="#item_9">
        <rdf:value>&lt;div data-schema-version=&quot;9&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;Uses the ZIP model with an extra component (accounting for frequency dependence of load power) and uses data of consumption types.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In face of a voltage collapse: when it clears, the PQ load returns faster to original power consumption than Z load. &amp;nbsp;However, load response also affects voltage recovery, which returns to higher voltage right after clearing when load is mostly Z. After that, local grid voltage oscillates against external grid, which causes P oscillation in Z load but not in PQ load. The Z load damps the voltage oscillation significantly better.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;a higher share of resistive loads, causes a higher voltage dependence and a lower active power overshoot. In contrast to this, the lowest voltages can be found for LU, since it has a high share of induction motors. The lower voltage dependence leads to a higher active power loading, which increases the voltage drop.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Z load has higher voltage damping.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When the transmission line is disconnected, voltage drops between 0.9 pu for Z loads and 0.88 pu for PQ loads. The proposed aggregate loads are distributed between. However, voltages below 0.9 pu may be critical during normal grid operation. Considering this, the relevance of the load behaviour becomes clear. Z loads stand for best-case conditions and PQ loads for the worst-case.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</rdf:value>
    </bib:Memo>
